As we monitor security attacks against us and \nothers and become aware of more frequent high-profile security breaches, we \nremain committed to implementing vigorous protections for any personal \ninformation we collect.\n\nOur efforts are managed by a global team of cybersecurity, IT, engineering, \noperations, and legal experts. A cybersecurity committee, driven by executive-\nlevel leaders, meets monthly to review metrics and evaluate emerging threats. To \nensure a robust breadth of knowledge, the team consults with external parties, \nsuch as computer security firms and risk management and governance experts. \n\nWe follow the processes to ensure information security management outlined \nin frameworks such as the ISO 27001 for Information Security Standards. We \naddress cybersecurity scenarios in our resilience planning, document them \nthrough business continuity plans, and test the reliability of our products and our \nability to respond to threats through attack simulations. Against the backdrop \nof frequent changes and fresh insights, we continually evaluate and evolve our \nsecurity measures. In the event of a cybersecurity issue, we’ve prescribed a \nset of actions for teams to initiate that will help us to determine the type and \nrigorousness of our response.  \n\nInformation security/cybersecurity awareness training is available on demand to all \nemployees, and we hold regular live trainings. Our IT team has implemented extensive \ntraining internally on the risks of phishing scam emails. This includes sending \nsimulated “attack” emails to all employees to test their awareness. The team provides \nfurther training for departments that have the least adequate responses.\n\nWHAT IT COVERS: \n\n > Technologies, processes, and \npractices designed to protect \nnetworks, computers, programs, and \ndata from cyberattack\n\n > Cybersecurity safeguards built into \n\nproduct design, implementation, and \nproduction\n\n > Protection of customer, employee, \n\nand company data\n\n > Compliance with cybersecurity and \n\ndata protection laws\n\nTable Of Contents\n\n  CYBERSECuRITY AND DATA PRIVACY  33\n\n2022 NVIDIA CORPORATE RESPONSIBILITY REPORT\x0c##PAGE_BREAK##The cybersecurity committee presents annually to NVIDIA’s Board of Directors \nand provides updates throughout the year. The team updates the Audit Committee \nupon request.  \n\nData Privacy\nWe continuously hone our cybersecurity and data privacy trainings and policies \nto respond to new requirements in global privacy laws. Our relationship with our \ncolleagues, customers, and business partners is based upon mutual trust. We’re \ncommitted to maintaining this trust by protecting the information we hold from \ninappropriate use, unauthorized access, loss, and accidental destruction. \n\nNVIDIA is governed by the following privacy policies, consistent with the Eu’s \ngeneral Data Protection Regulation (gDPR) principles and applied globally:\n\n > Our customer-facing NVIDIA Privacy Policy, which incorporates both a Cookie \n\nPolicy and a privacy policy aimed to protect children;\n\n > A collection of internal, corporate data privacy policies, focused on retention, \n\ndestruction, and encryption of data;\n\n > An Employee Privacy Policy and a Job Candidate Privacy Policy\n\nProduct Security\nNVIDIA takes security concerns seriously and works to evaluate and address them \nquickly. As soon as a security concern is reported, we commit all relevant \nresources to analyze, validate, and, if needed, provide corrective actions to address \nthe issue. NVIDIA Security Bulletins and Notices are published on our website.\n\nThe NVIDIA Product Security Incident Response Team (PSIRT) is a global team \nthat manages the receipt, investigation, internal coordination, remediation, \nand disclosure of security vulnerability information related to NVIDIA products \nand services. PSIRT’s goal is to minimize the risk to customers associated \nwith security vulnerabilities by providing timely information, guidance, and \nremediation of vulnerabilities in our products and services. The PSIRT team \nintegrates elements of the NIST Cybersecurity Framework and controls into its \nsecurity program. We participate in the global Forum of Incident Response and \nSecurity Teams (FIRST.org), contribute to FIRST.org Special Interest groups (SIgs) \nto make improvements to PSIRT processes, and share process knowledge with \nothers so they may implement this type of notification and security work within \ntheir own organizations.\n\nWe also participate in MITRE’s Cybersecurity and Vulnerability Exposure Number \nAuthority Coordination Working group and partner with third-party research \ninstitutions and corporate peers to extend the MITRE ATT&CK framework for AI to \nadvance the industry’s security and its response to new and upcoming threats. \n\nFIRST.ORG ACTIVITIES\nNVIDIA’s Shawn Richardson sits on \nthe Board of Directors of the Forum \nof Incident Response and Security \nTeams for the 2020-2022 term. We closely manage our supply \nchain to deliver innovative products that satisfy our customers’ expectations in \na socially and environmentally conscious manner.\n\nEnvironmental and Social Management\nWe have been Responsible Business Alliance (RBA) members since 2007 and \nin 2018 were accepted as Full Member. From the beginning, we adopted the \nRBA Code of Conduct and integrated its elements into our processes, including \nauditing strategic suppliers and conducting internal assessments to confirm that \nwe are addressing all aspects of responsible supply chain management.\n\nWe do not directly manufacture the semiconductor wafers or printed \ncircuit boards used in our products, nor do we manufacture our branded \ndevices. Instead, we partner with world-class suppliers for all phases of the \nmanufacturing process, including wafer fabrication, assembly, testing, and \npackaging. We also contract with manufacturers to build, test, and distribute our \nbranded devices.\n\nWe utilize industry-leading suppliers, such as Taiwan Semiconductor \nManufacturing Company Limited (TSMC) and Samsung Electronics Co. Ltd, to \nproduce our semiconductor wafers. Our two main contract manufacturers for \ncompany- or partner-branded devices are BYD Auto Co. Ltd. and Hon Hai Precision \nIndustry Co. (Foxconn). TSMC, Samsung, and Foxconn are RBA members. \n\nWHAT IT COVERS: \n\n > Policies and practices governing \n\nsupplier management, environmental \nand social impacts, and responsible \nsourcing of materials in the supply \nchain\n\n > Participation in industry \n\norganizations and engagement with \nsuppliers\n\n > Supplier audits to ensure compliance \n\nwith standards and requirements\n\n > Protection of human rights \nthroughout the supply chain\n\nTable Of Contents\n\n  SuPPLY CHAIN MANAgEMENT  35\n\n2022 NVIDIA CORPORATE RESPONSIBILITY REPORT\x0c##PAGE_BREAK##SUPPLIER COMPLIANCE\nNVIDIA communicates environmental \nand social expectations in the \nAgreement for Manufacturer \nEnvironmental Compliance, including:  \n\n > RBA’s Code of Conduct\n\n > global RoHS\n\n > Eu REACH \n\n > Eu End of Life Vehicles \n\n > JS709C & IEC61249-2-21\n\n > ISO 14001:2015 \n\n > ISO 27001:2013\n\n > ISO 45001:2018\n\nAll our manufacturing suppliers are required to comply with the RBA Code \nof Conduct and associated NVIDIA policies, including an Agreement for \nManufacturer Environmental Compliance. We also encourage them to use the \nRBA Code as a platform to go above and beyond compliance. \n\nOur assessment process involves using the RBA online system to evaluate \nexisting and potential new suppliers against product compliance industry \nstandards, social and environmental criteria, use of conflict minerals, the RBA \nCode, and NVIDIA’s code of conduct. We use the results of our assessment \nprocess, along with a spending analysis, to rank suppliers to determine their \noverall risk.\n\nStrategic suppliers include those who produce or handle NVIDIA production \nmaterials, those for whom we closely manage quality requirements (non-critical \nsuppliers), those who design our branded products, and those who we’re required \nto work with based on customer agreements. For strategic suppliers, agreements \nare deployed and tracked through a quarterly business review (QBR) process to \nmake certain that they uphold our requirements. QBR performance influences \nour business allocation decisions. Each quarter, we review overall supplier \nassessment by product category and rank performance. Five of 100 QBR points \nare allocated to environmental or social performance, and requirements vary by \nquarter. Suppliers are required to meet industry compliance requirements as well \nas NVIDIA requirements. We’ve assessed and adjusted business with suppliers \nwho don’t comply with minimum requirements.\n\nIn FY20, we reviewed all strategic suppliers against NVIDIA cybersecurity \nrequirements, and in FY21, we performed a more in-depth assessment of \nhigher-risk suppliers. We looked at our suppliers’ conformance to ISO 27001, \nISO 28001, and C-TPAT standards, and evaluated them for additional information, \nproduct, and physical security requirements. Depending on the results of the \nassessment, we require additional evidence of conformance or an improvement \nplan if gaps are discovered. \n\nWe began using Bitsight in FY22 to provide continuous monitoring of cybersecurity \nrisks in our supply chain. Suppliers are reviewed on a variety of topics and \nreceive a low-, moderate-, or high-risk rating, which we then use to implement \nimprovements. Our goal is to use \nonly conflict-free gold, tantalum, tungsten, and tin (3Tg) in our products, and to \nachieve 100% Responsible Minerals Assurance Process compliant tantalum, tin, \ntungsten, and gold processing facilities (approximately 90%). We share an annual \nupdate in our Conflict Minerals Report, which can be found on our website. We’ve \nsuccessfully removed non-compliant 3Tg smelters and refiners in our supply \nchain to help us meet this goal.\n\nWe’re a member of the Public Private Alliance (PPA) for Responsible Minerals \nTrade and the RBA’s Responsible Minerals Initiative (RMI). The PPA provides \nfunding and coordination support to organizations working within the Democratic \nRepublic of Congo and adjacent countries to develop verifiable conflict-free supply \nchains, align due diligence programs and practices, encourage responsible \nsourcing from the region, promote transparency, and bolster in-region civil \nsociety and governmental capacity. We support these on-the-ground programs \naimed at improving transparency for responsible sourcing and reducing human \nrights risks, including forced labor. Our due diligence program regarding conflict \nmaterials conforms in all material respects with the framework recommended by \nthe Organization for Economic Cooperation and Development (OECD). \n\nOur Responsible Minerals Policy, sourcing goals, and the steps we take to \nmonitor our supply chain for conflict minerals is framed around the OECD Due \nDiligence guidance for Responsible Supply Chains of Minerals from Conflict-\nAffected and High-Risk Areas. This guidance provides detailed recommendations \nto help companies respect human rights and avoid contributing to conflict \nthrough their mineral purchasing decisions and practices. Our due diligence \nprogram regarding conflict materials conforms in all material respects with the \nframework recommended by the OECD.\n\nWe continue to evaluate smelter metrics for annual SEC conflict minerals \nreporting requirements, and we remove or deactivate suppliers that are non-\ncompliant with product and conflict mineral requirements. During the reporting \nperiod, 100% of our suppliers and component manufacturers responded with the \nrequested information. \n\nTable Of Contents\n\n  SuPPLY CHAIN MANAgEMENT  39\n\n2022 NVIDIA CORPORATE RESPONSIBILITY REPORT\x0c##PAGE_BREAK##Additionally, we participate in various RMI work groups and align our program \nwith the organization’s tracking of additional minerals and materials and with \ngeographic areas of high concern. NVIDIA accelerates this revolution \nby creating advanced computing tools that serve as open platforms for \ndevelopers, researchers, and data scientists to innovate in these areas. \n\nThe responsibilities associated with designing technologies that enable a better \nworld are deeply rooted in our values. Our commitment to developing trusted AI \nthat is rooted in the principles of upholding human rights is outlined below, along \nwith an overview of how we enable a pipeline of future talent to have a rewarding \ncareer in AI and see the potential they have in using AI to solve some of society’s \nmost challenging problems.\n\nTRUSTWORTHY AI\n\nWe're committed to the advancement of Trustworthy AI (TAI), founded in \nprinciples that reflect our core values and the fundamentals in our Code of \nConduct. Recognizing that technology can have a profound impact on people and \nthe world, we’ve set priorities that are rooted in fostering positive change and \nenabling trust and transparency in AI development.\n\nTo realize re-usable and interchangeable high-quality, trustworthy AI \ncomponents, we are developing practices and methodologies enabling \nconstruction of “trustworthy by design” AI products. Practices and methodologies \nspan collection and use of datasets, machine learning tools and processes, AI \nmodel development, and software development and testing.  \n\nTable Of Contents\n\n  SOCIETAL IMPACTS OF AI  41\n\n2022 NVIDIA CORPORATE RESPONSIBILITY REPORT\x0c##PAGE_BREAK##Scope and Governance \nThe scope of our global TAI program is focused on the elements involved in \ndeveloping and deploying an AI model or system and involves integrating \nmethodologies from our product life cycle development process into machine \nlearning models, datasets, SDKs, and frameworks authored by NVIDIA.  We train \ndevelopers, engineers, and researchers, and host sessions on TAI practices for \nbusiness and civic leaders at our developer conferences.\n\nWe have established internal principles, influenced by our corporate values and \nleveraging global frameworks (such as the Eu’s High-Level Expert group on \nArtificial Intelligence and Singapore’s Model Artificial Intelligence governance \nFramework), into every stage of developing and deploying an AI model or system \n– from concept to performance validation to decommission. We participate in \nindustry-specific working groups, as well as standards bodies such as the IEEE \nOrganizational governance of Artificial Intelligence Working group. \n\nOur TAI efforts are led by a head of Trustworthy AI and supported by a cross-\nfunctional committee and teams aligned with each of our principles. These teams \nare responsible for integrating “trustworthiness by design” into our existing \nproduct development processes and for building tools and systems to assess \nproduct performance. Our global public policy team monitors global regulations \nand relevant standards to ensure we maintain compliance.\n\nSee Upholding Human Rights for how we evaluate risk to vulnerable populations \nand conduct due diligence on customer use of our AI products. \n\nModel Risk Management \nNVIDIA aims to reduce the risk of harm from deployment of AI models or systems. \nModel risk can come from many sources including, but not limited to: datasets \nused to train the model, malicious attacks against the model, or failure to comply \nwith laws and regulations.  \n\nOur model risk management guidance outlines to all employees working on \nmodels the elements of development, validation, audit, and documentation, \nspecifically: \n\n > Translates our principles into actionable product life cycle requirements which \n\nwill be integrated into our larger Product Lifecycle process;\n\n > Outlines the key steps to identify, measure, manage, and mitigate potential \nrisks associated with our AI and machine learning models and systems; and\n\n > Is aligned with and incorporates the Company’s privacy guidance as a \n\npragmatic approach to compliance.  \n\nThis approach provides internal development teams with guidance to achieve an \ninnovative, yet ethically responsible solution.   \n\nWe’ve designed several tools for internal developers to aid in the creation of \ntrustworthy AI models:  \n\nWHAT GOES INTO BUILDING \nTRUSTWORTHY TECHNOLOGY?\nRead a conversation between \nNVIDIA’s Nikki Pope, senior \ndirector for AI and legal ethics, and \nBeena Ammanath, Deloitte LLP’s \nTrustworthy and Ethical Technology \nleader, on the challenges around \ncreating trustworthy AI.\n\nTable Of Contents\n\n  SOCIETAL IMPACTS OF AI  42\n\n2022 NVIDIA CORPORATE RESPONSIBILITY REPORT\x0c##PAGE_BREAK## > An inspection dashboard where the company's commercial models are \n\nregistered, which measures a model’s completion of essential steps prior to \npublication and includes a current performance score and a target goal;\n\n > Model requirements and dataset approval process, that models must meet \n\nprior to commercial release; We emphasize the importance of \nsupporting positive uses of AI while considering issues inherent in its development.\n\nUPHOLDING HUMAN RIGHTS\n\nWe believe AI will enhance human welfare and human rights in a myriad of ways. \nNVIDIA is accelerating this revolution by creating platforms and computing tools \nthat help developers, researchers, and data scientists innovate in these areas. \n\nOur products are programmable and general purpose in nature. When we provide \ntools to help developers create applications for specific industries, we focus on \ncreating products and services that enable developers to create and accelerate \nsocially beneficial applications that will promote human welfare everywhere.  \n\nThe NCgC has oversight over policies and practices in connection with human \nrights. The NCgC undertakes all actions it deems reasonable and necessary \nto ensure compliance with our Human Rights Policy, conducting regular \nconsultation with a cross-functional business, legal, and technical team within \nNVIDIA, including senior-level management, and seeking input from third-party \nstakeholders and experts. The NCgC provides regular updates to the entire Board \nof Directors regarding human rights impacts and compliance.\n\nWe are committed to facilitating access to effective justice and remedy. \nAnyone, including employees, suppliers and other external stakeholders, can \nconfidentially and anonymously report a concern about human rights using a \ncorporate hotline that is hosted by an independent third party.\n\nunder the direction of the NCgC, our Compliance Committee will promptly \ninvestigate human rights allegations and pursue actions to mitigate and \nremediate any adverse human rights impacts. We do not tolerate retaliation \nagainst anyone for making a complaint in good faith, bringing a potential violation \nto the attention of management, or participating or assisting in an investigation.\n\nHUMAN RIGHTS PRINCIPLES \nWe follow the laws of the countries \nin which we operate, and endorse \ninternationally recognized principles, \nincluding:\n\n > United Nations Global Compact \n\n > United Nations Guiding Principles\n\n > Universal Declaration of Human \n\nRights\n\n > International Covenant on Civil and \n\nPolitical Rights\n\n > International Covenant on \n\nEconomic, Social and Cultural \nRights\n\n > Core Conventions of the \n\nInternational Labour Organization\n\n > ILO Declaration on Fundamental \n\nPrinciples and Rights at Work\n\nTable Of Contents\n\n  SOCIETAL IMPACTS OF AI  43\n\n2022 NVIDIA CORPORATE RESPONSIBILITY REPORT\x0c##PAGE_BREAK##BUILDING A DIVERSE AI TALENT \nPIPELINE\n\nImproving the representation of women and other underrepresented communities \nin technology requires a long-term perspective, so we support opportunities \nthat provide youth access to STEM and AI education. We aim to make every new \ngeneration of gPus faster and more energy efficient than its predecessor.\n\nAnd our technology is driving some of the most important advances for modeling \nour climate, reducing carbon emissions, and designing mitigation and adaptation \nstrategies in a changing world. \n\nARCHITECTURE ENERGY EFFICIENCY \n\nAI is revolutionizing scientific computing, and our platform enables modern data \ncenters to accelerate increasingly common deep learning, machine learning, \nand high-performance computing (HPC) workloads. gPu-accelerated computing \nmoves compute-intensive sections of the applications to the gPu while remaining \nsections execute in the CPu. As a result, sequential calculations are performed in \nthe CPu while the more complicated matrix calculations are computed in parallel \nin the gPu, consuming less power than the equivalent, traditional computational \nforms relying on CPus.\n\nWe aim to make every generation of gPus faster and more energy efficient than \nits predecessor. NVIDIA Ampere architecture is up to 20x faster for AI training \nand inference and up to 7.5x more energy efficient than its previous generation. \n\nWHAT IT COVERS: \n\n > Energy efficiency considerations \n\nbuilt into product design \n\n > Energy efficiency and performance \n\nimprovements of each new \ngeneration of products\n\n > Software and networking to optimize \n\nenergy efficiency and performance\n\n > Applications of NVIDIA technology \nfor climate change mitigation and \nadaptation\n\nTable Of Contents\n\n2022 NVIDIA CORPORATE RESPONSIBILITY REPORT\n\n  ENVIRONMENTAL INITIATIVES AND PARTNERSHIPS  46\n\n\x0c##PAGE_BREAK##12 TRILLION\n\nThe world could save nearly 12 \ntrillion watt-hours of energy a year \nby switching CPu-only servers to \ngPu-accelerated servers for AI  \nand HPC.\n\nOur Hopper gPu architecture, announced in March 2022, is up to 30x faster for AI \ninference and up to 3.5x more energy efficient than NVIDIA Ampere architecture, \nwhich it succeeds.\n\nAI Performance and Efficiency\nWe put trained models to work in live applications run by millions of hyperscale \nservers worldwide. Our TensorRT inference software helps even the largest \nneural networks run across a broad range of data center, embedded, and \nautomotive applications in real time. \n\nThe MLPerf consortium provides an industry benchmark for AI performance and \nenergy efficiency on scientific applications in HPC. In its debut, our Orin system-\non-chip based on NVIDIA Ampere architecture set new records in AI inference and \nled in five of six performance tests. Along with our partners, we continue to show \nleading performance across all tests and scenarios in the MLPerf inference round. \n\nEnergy efficiency is critical as AI models and HPC applications increase \nexponentially in size. By moving to new-generation gPus, our customers complete \ntheir work with lower energy consumption and get results back more quickly.  \n\nIndividual gPus typically have a higher peak active power consumption than \nCPus, but also complete workloads dramatically faster, so they return to low \npower idle states quickly and thus consume far less overall energy. NVIDIA gPus \nare typically 20x more energy efficient for AI and HPC workloads than CPus. If \nwe switched all the CPu-only servers running AI and HPC worldwide to gPu-\naccelerated systems, the world could save nearly 12 trillion watt-hours of energy \na year, equivalent to the electricity requirements of nearly 1.7 million u.S. homes.\n\nSupercomputer Efficiency\nProcessing capabilities have grown exponentially in the past decade - fueled \nlargely by supercomputers, data centers and cloud computing. With the fully \ndeveloped end-to-end hardware and software stack, the NVIDIA accelerated \ncomputing platform is the engine of the modern data center. \n\nNVIDIA powers 23 of the top 30 supercomputers on the June 2022 green500 list. \nA hyperscale data center with NVIDIA gPus takes up 1/47th of the rack space of \nthe CPu-based systems that it replaces and runs at 93% lower energy cost for AI \nmodels.\n\nWe develop hardware, software, and networking technology to improve \nperformance and energy efficiency in the data center. We provide customers \ninsight into server level power efficiency to enable users to run workloads with \nan optimal balance of performance and power efficiency.  \n\nSOFTWARE OPTIMIZATIONS\nSoftware can significantly improve energy efficiency of AI workloads. We’re \ncontinuously optimizing our CUDA-X libraries and GPU-accelerated applications, \nso it’s not unusual for users to see an x-factor performance gain on the same gPu \narchitecture. AI workloads on NVIDIA Ampere architecture improved by 2.5x over \nthe past two years.  \n\nTable Of Contents\n\n2022 NVIDIA CORPORATE RESPONSIBILITY REPORT\n\n  ENVIRONMENTAL INITIATIVES AND PARTNERSHIPS  47\n\n\x0c##PAGE_BREAK##We offer the latest versions of AI and HPC software from the NVIDIA gPu \nCloud (NgC) to help users run applications at higher performance on their \nsupercomputer, in the data center, or in the cloud. We estimate energy savings of \n20% on NgC workloads because of users implementing performance suggestions \nfrom tools like Pytorch Performance Linter, which optimize models and input-\noutput pipelines.\n\nNETWORKING BOOSTS\nAs supercomputers take on more workloads across data analytics, AI, \nsimulation and visualization, CPus are stretched to support a growing number \nof communication tasks needed to operate large and complex systems. Data \nprocessing units (DPUs), which move data around the data center, alleviate 30% \nor more of this stress by offloading some of these processes from the CPu. \nCertain workloads achieve more than 50x performance improvement, allowing \nfewer servers to be deployed and reducing power of a modest datacenter by 4MW. \nThe zero-trust protection platform enabled by NVIDIA DPus brings a new level of \nsecurity to data centers at speeds up to 600x faster than servers without NVIDIA \naccelerations, again reducing infrastructure and power.\n\nBuilt for AI, the NVIDIA Spectrum-4 Ethernet switch enables extreme networking \nperformance and robust security with 40% lower power consumption compared \nto the previous generation.\n\nCOOLING IMPROVEMENTS\nAdequate cooling is required to optimize supercomputer performance. We \ndeploy state-of-the-art technology designed for NVIDIA server products, using \ncomputational fluid dynamics models to enhance cooling for data center designs \nand server rack deployments. Cooling solutions are closely coupled with server \nracks to localize and optimize heat transfer. \n\nWe share our data center best practices with customers and partners to help \noptimize their deployments. In partnership with leading storage and networking \ntechnology providers, we offer a portfolio of reference architectures for optimal \nand efficient deployment of our DgX server products, and we make these publicly \navailable on our corporate website.  \n\nGaming Efficiency\nMax-Q is a system design approach that enables thin and light gaming laptops to \ndeliver high performance with optimal efficiency. Every component and element \nof the laptop—from gPu, CPu, and software to PCB design, power delivery, and \nthermals—is optimized for power efficiency and performance.\n\nDynamic Boost 2.0 uses AI to balance power among the CPu, gPu, and gPu \nmemory, reducing power consumption by about 20-25%. It is available on all \ngeForce RTX 30 Series Max-Q laptops and is enabled out of the box, helping \nmaximize performance in every app and game. \n\nDesktop-class geForce RTX 30 Series graphics cards offer up to 2x the \nperformance and 1.9x the power efficiency over the previous generation.  \n\nTable Of Contents\n\n2022 NVIDIA CORPORATE RESPONSIBILITY REPORT\n\n  ENVIRONMENTAL INITIATIVES AND PARTNERSHIPS  48\n\n\x0c##PAGE_BREAK##ACCELERATING CLIMATE ACTION \n\nClimate scientists in government labs and universities have long used gPus to \nmodel climate scenarios and predict weather patterns. With recent advances in \nAI, modeling of weather forecasting can now be done 4-5 magnitudes faster than \nby using traditional methods.  \n\nWe announced plans to build Earth-2, an AI supercomputer dedicated to \npredicting the impacts of climate change. The system will build a digital twin of \nthe Earth on Omniverse, enabling scientists to do ultra-high-resolution climate \nmodeling and put mitigation and adaptation tools into the hands of cities and \nnations so they can act with more urgency.  \n\nIn the commercial sector, AI-driven power grid operations and next-generation \nsmart meters are enabling utilities to accelerate the world’s energy transition. \nOur Omniverse platform is being used to simulate digital twins that predict costly \nmaintenance at power plants and model new energy sources such as fusion \nreactor design. \n\nSupporting Global Climate Strategies\nAI Nations is NVIDIA’s global effort to democratize AI by supporting governments \nand related stakeholders in developing plans to implement AI strategies that \nadvance national priorities and drive economic growth. Managing climate-related \ndisasters is a pressing priority for most countries, and NVIDIA’s significant \ncompute power combined with its tools and expertise can help nations accelerate \na response to country-specific climate impacts more quickly.\n\nIn FY23 we announced a partnership with the united Nations Satellite Center \n(uNOSAT) to promote the use of AI for Earth observation (AI4EO) activities in \nsupport of the Sustainable Development Goals, with an emphasis on disaster \nmanagement. The collaboration aims to integrate NVIDIA’s accelerated computing \nplatform within uNOSAT’s infrastructure to fast-track research and development \nof AI4EO efforts. And through the design and roll-out of an online course on the \nuse of deep learning for flood detection, we plan to upskill data scientists within \ndisaster management agencies worldwide.\n\nNVIDIA Inception Partners\nOur Inception program is designed to nurture cutting-edge startups through \ngo-to-market support, expertise, and technology. Inception includes over 10,000 \ncompanies from 110 countries, many of which are demonstrating how daunting \nclimate challenges can be better understood and addressed with AI. Examples of \nareas where these startups are leveraging NVIDIA technology to have an impact \ninclude harnessing satellite data for environmental monitoring and climate \nrisk assessment, tracking wildlife poaching and illegal trafficking, analyzing \nglobal-scale maritime data to inform innovation around natural ocean carbon \nsinks, renewable energy, and shipping route optimization, analyzing water \ninfrastructure, and much more.\n\nEMISSIONS REDUCTION  \nIN ACTION \nIn FY22, we hosted a panel of energy \nsector leaders at gTC on how the \nindustry can work together to reduce \ncarbon emissions. \n\nTable Of Contents\n\n2022 NVIDIA CORPORATE RESPONSIBILITY REPORT\n\n  ENVIRONMENTAL INITIATIVES AND PARTNERSHIPS  49\n\n\x0c##PAGE_BREAK##10\nCLIMATE CHANgE \nMANAgEMENT\n\nIn the area of sustainability, we address our climate impacts across our product \nlifecycle and assess risks, including current and emerging regulations and \nmarket impacts. \n\nBy the end of the fiscal year ending January 31, 2025, we plan to purchase or \ngenerate enough renewable energy to match 100% of our global electricity usage \nfor our offices and data centers.\n\nWhether it is creation of technology to power next-generation laptops or designs \nto support high-performance supercomputers, addressing climate change by \nimproving energy efficiency is important in our research, development, and \ndesign processes. Our current goal to source all global electricity \nuse for offices and data centers from renewable energy will result in a 100% \nemissions reduction of our scope 2 emissions by end of FY25.\n\nWith our expanding business and diversification into new online services, data \ncenter operations have been growing rapidly. Data centers were responsible for \n54% of our total energy use in FY22, with offices making up the remainder. As \nwe expand, we’re incorporating renewable energy and energy efficiency into the \nsiting and design of new buildings under our ownership, and we consider energy \nefficiency, renewable energy availability, and other sustainability attributes when \nevaluating new leased spaces. \n\nIn the last three years, we’ve newly secured renewable power for several \ncolocation data centers both in the united States and globally. In FY22, we \nconducted an energy-efficiency study to understand the effect of converting an \nair-cooled data center system to hybrid air/liquid and seek to incorporate the \nresults into future projects. \n\nOur Silicon Valley headquarters in Santa Clara, CA, is LEED gold certified. It was \ndesigned with high levels of energy efficiency in mind, including a high-performing \nbuilding envelope, efficient and smart lighting systems that incorporate the use of \ndaylight, underfloor air distribution, radiant heating and cooling, air and waterside \neconomizers, and high-efficiency boilers and chillers. An advanced building control \nsystem underpins the building’s operation. \n\nWe’re also planning for LEED gold certification for a second building at our \nheadquarters. In addition to similarly advanced levels of energy- and water-\nefficient design, this building features biophilic elements and a shade-providing \nexternal trellis that will house 390 kW of solar panels to harness Santa Clara's \nsunny weather. A three-acre park filled with drought-tolerant trees and greenery \nfed by reclaimed water connect the two headquarters buildings.\n\nDATA CENTER SUSTAINABILITY\nIn FY22, we saw new renewable \nenergy supply contracts come \nonline at our supercomputer site in \nCambridge, u.K., and data centers \nin Reno, NV. Approximately a third of \nNVIDIA data centers around the world \nsourced electricity from renewable \nsources.\n\nTable Of Contents\n\n  CLIMATE CHANgE MANAgEMENT  52\n\n2022 NVIDIA CORPORATE RESPONSIBILITY REPORT\x0c##PAGE_BREAK##FLEXIBLE WORKSPACES\nAcross our global offices, we are \nimplementing a flexible working \narrangement to support to utilize our \nspace more effectively and improve \nour HVAC and electrical efficiency.\n\nWe continuously upgrade facilities and infrastructure to improve the energy \nefficiency of existing buildings. The program includes 61 electric vehicle charging stations, \npre-tax dollars for transit and local transit shuttles, and an online resource for \ncommuters. For cyclists, we provide lockers, showers, and secure bike parking. \nTo assist our alternative commuters in the event of an emergency, we offer an \nemergency ride home program through ride-sharing services.\n\nMost of our employees have been working remotely since the COVID-19 pandemic \nhit in March 2020. Working from home reduced the need for commuting \nprograms and business travel. As we support hybrid onsite and at-home work \narrangements, commute and business travel patterns change or are not needed, \nthereby decreasing our carbon footprint. For more information about how we’ve \nsupported employees working from home, see COVID-19 Support.\n\nWATER USED IN OPERATIONS\nWe use water in our direct operations in cooling towers and for food service, \nlandscaping, and sanitation. We take steps to use water efficiently, particularly in \nlocations that are vulnerable to drought conditions, such as California and Israel, \nwhere we have large facilities. As we develop and grow at our headquarters, we’re \nimplementing measures to conserve water resources and reduce our potable \nwater demand. We first conducted a water risk assessment in 2018 and update \nit annually for all NVIDIA facilities, third-party data centers, and strategic supply \nchain partners. This helps us target water conservation initiatives to locations \nwhere they are most needed.\n\nOur two headquarter buildings in Santa Clara, CA, incorporate a range of water \nconservation measures. Through the installation of low-flow bathroom fixtures \nand the use of recycled water for toilet flushing, the buildings are designed to \nachieve over 40% reduction in domestic water demand and a 50% reduction in \npotable water use for sewage conveyance. We use reclaimed water in cooling \ntowers and landscape irrigation systems, and our landscaping consists of native, \ndrought-resistant plants. \n\nWe upgrade fixtures and appliances to improve efficiency and conserve water. Our \nHyderabad, India, site has a water treatment plant that reuses the site’s treated \nwastewater for landscape irrigation. In FY22, we constructed a bioswale to \ncapture rainwater in Santa Clara. \n\nWATER\nWater withdrawal (cubic meters)\n\ngroundwater\n\nMunicipal water supplies\n\nReclaimed water from another organization\n\nWater consumption (cubic meters)\n\nWater discharge (cubic meters)\n\nFY22\n817,082a\n\n0b\n\n666,560\n\n150,522\n\n394,477\n\n422,605\n\nFY21\n365,450\n\n40,041\n\n269,782\n\n50,078\n\n97,263\n\n268,186\n\nFY20\n322,081\n\n4,136\n\n279,819\n\n53,964\n\n94,698\n\n227,383\n\na  Starting in FY22, water withdrawal, consumption, and discharge includes estimated use by data centers.\nb  Starting in FY22, the site that reported groundwater is counted in municipal water supplies.\n\nTable Of Contents\n\n  CLIMATE CHANgE MANAgEMENT  54\n\n2022 NVIDIA CORPORATE RESPONSIBILITY REPORT\x0c##PAGE_BREAK##As a fabless company, we rely on our suppliers to manufacture our products. CORPORATE RESPONSIBILITY REPORT\x0c##PAGE_BREAK##93% \n\nOverall recyclability rate for all \npackaging.\n\nSupplier Environmental Impact\nBecause emissions are created at every stage of our product lifecycle, including \nmanufacturing within our supply chain, beginning in 2014 we’ve required our key \nsuppliers to report their energy usage, gHg emissions data, and reduction goals \nand objectives. \n\nThese suppliers must also have their gHg emissions verified by a third party. \nWe track suppliers’ annual energy, gHg, water, and waste through the CDP and \nRBA Environmental Survey for all silicon manufacturers and systems contract \nmanufacturers. We use this supplier data to better understand our product \nmanufacturing impact, determine carbon emissions and water consumption per \nfinancial outlay, and to allocate carbon emissions to our customers.\n\nIn FY21, we surveyed our suppliers to better understand the renewable energy \nperformance and capability of our manufacturing supply chain. We plan to re-\nsurvey our suppliers in FY23 and use this as a benchmark moving forward.\n\nProduct Packaging\nWe continuously improve the balance between protecting the environment and \nensuring that our customers receive their products in immaculate condition. We \nembrace opportunities to reduce packing materials and increase the proportion \nof recycled, recyclable, and biodegradable materials used. Whether products are \npackaged for end-users or prepared for bulk shipping, we design our containers \nto maximize package density and reduce overall package size.  \n\nOur bulk carton packaging uses corrugate material that is 100% recycled \nfibers, and the cartons maintain an overall recyclability rate of 100%. Consumer \npackaging uses 70% recycled fibers and maintains a recyclability rate above 75%. \n\nOur packaging sustainability initiatives include:\n\n > Developing smaller and lighter weight packaging; \n\n > Creating a “core box” system so that primary retail packaging and shipping \n\ncarton boxes can be shared among product SKus; \n\n > using recycled HDPE-2, which is recyclable, in place of polystyrene material \n\nwherever plastics are required; \n\n > Removing plastic film lamination or replacing it with recyclable material; \n\n > Leveraging vegetable oil-based inks and water-based solutions;\n\n > Switching plastic tray and foam components to paper-based materials where \n\nwe can; and\n\n > Applying material labels to all packages to simplify consumer recycling.\n\nFor our DgX server products, which require shipping in large cardboard boxes or \ncrates with protective foam, we aim to maximize recyclability by eliminating the \nuse of wood and metal, switching to corrugate or corrugate-strawboard hybrid \nstructures, and minimizing the use of foams by utilizing HDPE-2 cushioning systems. \n\nAs a result, we maintain an overall recyclability rate above 93% for all packaging. \n\nTo reduce the amount of packaging used, we reuse packaging, ship products \ndirectly to the retail distributor, and use existing packaging for return \nmerchandise authorization support whenever possible. We also reduce paper by \nproviding online instructions for both our retail and server packages.\n\nTable Of Contents\n\n  CLIMATE CHANgE MANAgEMENT  56\n\n2022 NVIDIA CORPORATE RESPONSIBILITY REPORT\x0c##PAGE_BREAK##Our key packaging suppliers are compliant with NVIDIA’s environmental \nrequirements for Forestry Stewardship Council, Halogen Free, REACH, and ROHS. \n\nTransport and Logistics\nHow we plan, pack, and execute our raw material, work-in-progress, and \nfinished-goods shipments impacts our scope 3 emissions. Fuel represents \na significant portion of our overall freight costs, and our continuous focus on \noptimizing our transport and logistics has resulted in cost savings and lessened \nour impact on the environment. Improvements include: \n\n > Configuring primary and subcontractor packing that minimizes the shipping \n\nfootprint and reduces the number of pickups and deliveries;\n\n > Reducing overall packaging and shipment weights where possible;\n\n > Implementing a multimodal (ocean/truck) distribution and replenishment \n\nsystem globally where possible;\n\n > Requiring suppliers to report their participation in environmental initiatives \n\nquarterly; and\n\n > using reverse logistics solutions that use onsite or regional failure verification \n\nand repair to streamline product returns and eliminate international shipments. \n\nWe gather data from packaging and shipping partners related to the carbon \nemissions of our packaging production and shipments from air, land, and sea.  \n\nProduct End-of-Life Management  \nMore regional, national, and sub-national governments are regulating the \ndisposal of electrical and electronic equipment waste by placing the responsibility \nfor end-of-life management on the producer of the equipment. NVIDIA-branded \nproducts, such as our SHIELD gaming devices, are subject to such requirements \nin our various global markets, and we take seriously our extended responsibility \nfor these products. In key regions such as the united States and Europe, we’ve \nestablished recycling programs in partnership with reputable third parties and \nwe provide information to consumers about how to recycle our branded products, \nincluding through our product recycling page.\n\nIn FY22 we launched a pilot program to help our customers monetize the potential \nresidual value in the older DgX servers when refreshing to the latest technology. \nSome of the servers are refurbished, then sold or donated for reuse. Alternatively, \nthey’re sold as components in the secondary market.\n\nTable Of Contents\n\n  CLIMATE CHANgE MANAgEMENT  57\n\n2022 NVIDIA CORPORATE RESPONSIBILITY REPORT\x0c##PAGE_BREAK##11\nREPORTINg FRAMEWORKS\n\nGRI INDEX\n\nWe applied the internationally recognized global Reporting Initiative (gRI) Sustainability Reporting Standards to produce this \nFY22 Corporate Responsibility Report. Stanford \nuniversity School of Medicine led an initiative to cut down the time needed to sequence and \nanalyze a patient’s genome from days to hours, setting the first guinness World Record for \nfastest DNA sequencing technique. The researchers used NVIDIA Tensor Core gPus in a google \nCloud computing environment and NVIDIA Clara Parabricks. \n\nSafer Roads—Startup Derq uses NVIDIA gPus to process video and other data from cameras and \nradars to better predict crashes before they happen and to warn connected road users. Another \nstartup, CVEDIA, taps the NVIDIA TAO Toolkit to design better and faster vehicle and pedestrian \ndetections to improve traffic flow and pedestrian safety. \n\nAI Pathways Institute—Teens with the Boys & girls Clubs of Hudson County in northeastern New \nJersey spent three weeks in 2021 brainstorming, coding, and traversing spinning robots while \nusing NVIDIA Jetson Nano 2gB developer kits and Jetbot robotics toolkits to aid patients with \nAlzheimer’s, discard trash, monitor pedestrian safety, and track outdoor air pollution.\n\nGrants for Developer Kits—As part of a grant program, we gave hundreds of Jetson Nano \ndeveloper kits to educators in colleges, schools, and nonprofit groups. We also certify students \nand educators in AI skills through NVIDIA Deep Learning Institute (DLI).\n\nAI Innovation in Africa—Our head of emerging areas gave a keynote speech at AI Expo Africa, \nhighlighting the AI revolution and sharing how NVIDIA supports developers to build and scale their \nAI projects through the NVIDIA Developer Program, Inception Program, and DLI. \n\nVenture Capital Funding Opportunities—The NVIDIA Inception VC Alliance opens new paths for \nstartups to engage, create introductions, and accelerate potential funding, which will facilitate \nglobal innovation. The new benefit offers connections for 200 venture capital firms and investors \nto 10,000+ startups working in AI, data science, HPC, and more.\n\nInclusion in AI—At gTC in April 2021, we hosted speakers to discuss AI literacy and efforts to grow \nthe participation of underrepresented groups in science and engineering. In November 2021, we \nled a panel discussion on how to get more women into AI and data science.\n\nNVIDIA Emerging Chapters—This program aims to mend what’s called the technology fracture—\nthe gap between developers in the global North and those in emerging markets—by supporting \nlocal communities to build and scale their AI, data science, and graphics projects to solve relevant \nchallenges. Program members also have access to training and development opportunities \nthrough the NVIDIA DLI. \n\nEarth-2 Supercomputer—At gTC in November 2021, NVIDIA CEO Jensen Huang announced plans \nto build a powerful AI supercomputer dedicated to predicting climate change. We’ll bring our \nscale and expertise in computational sciences to join with the world’s climate science community \nto confront climate change.\n\nSustainability Investments in India—Our corporate social responsibility investments in India are \npart of multiyear efforts in the country focused on investing in social innovation, job creation, and \nbiodiversity. We support projects to build water-harvesting structures, plant local, non-invasive \ntrees, improve soil health, and reduce open-field burning.\n\nTable Of Contents\n\n  REPORTINg FRAMEWORKS  67\n\n2022 NVIDIA CORPORATE RESPONSIBILITY REPORT\x0c##PAGE_BREAK##ABOuT THIS REPORT\n\nThe information contained in this report is accurate as \nof approximately July 7, 2022, unless stated otherwise. \nThe information is subject to change, and NVIDIA will \nnot necessarily disclose such changes. Natural Language Processing¶

Extracting content by pages and sentences¶

  1. Only properly structured sentences are extracted. Sentences that start with a Capital Letter and ends with a period. Sentences that are less than 10 words or more than 50 words are ignored.
  2. Pages with less than 500 words are excluded from extraction. Would like to focus on pages with mostly text content. This should exclude pages like cover and last page. It should also exclude pages that are more graphical with short notes and comments.
In [23]:
def remove_non_ascii(text):
    printable = set(string.printable)
    return ''.join(filter(lambda x: x in printable, text))

def not_header(line):
    # as we're consolidating broken lines into paragraphs, we want to make sure not to include headers
    return not line.isupper()

def extract_sentences(nlp, text):
    """
    Extracting ESG statements from raw text by removing junk, URLs, etc.
    We group consecutive lines into paragraphs and use spacy to parse sentences.
    """
    MIN_WORDS_PER_PAGE = 500
    
    pages = text.split('##PAGE_BREAK##')
#     print('Number of Pages: {}'.format(len(pages)))

    lines = []
    for page in pages:
        
        # remove non ASCII characters
        text = remove_non_ascii(page)
        
        if len(text.split(' ')) < MIN_WORDS_PER_PAGE:
#             print('Skipped Page: {}'.format(len(text.split(' '))))
            continue
        
        prev = ""
        for line in text.split('\n\n'):
            # aggregate consecutive lines where text may be broken down
            # only if next line starts with a space or previous does not end with dot.
            if(line.startswith(' ') or not prev.endswith('.')):
                prev = prev + ' ' + line
            else:
                # new paragraph
                lines.append(prev)
                prev = line

        # don't forget left-over paragraph
        lines.append(prev)
        lines.append('##SAME_PAGE##')
        
    lines = '  '.join(lines).split('##SAME_PAGE##')
    
    # clean paragraphs from extra space, unwanted characters, urls, etc.
    # best effort clean up, consider a more versatile cleaner
    
    sentences = []
    pages_content = []

    for line in lines[:-1]:
        # removing header number
        line = re.sub(r'^\s?\d+(.*)$', r'\1', line)
        # removing trailing spaces
        line = line.strip()
        # words may be split between lines, ensure we link them back together
        line = re.sub(r'\s?-\s?', '-', line)
        # remove space prior to punctuation
        line = re.sub(r'\s?([,:;\.])', r'\1', line)
        # ESG contains a lot of figures that are not relevant to grammatical structure
        line = re.sub(r'\d{5,}', r' ', line)
        # remove emails
        line = re.sub(r'\S*@\S*\s?', '', line)
        # remove mentions of URLs
        line = re.sub(r'((http|https)\:\/\/)?[a-zA-Z0-9\.\/\?\:@\-_=#]+\.([a-zA-Z]){2,6}([a-zA-Z0-9\.\&\/\?\:@\-_=#])*', r' ', line)
        # remove multiple spaces
        line = re.sub(r'\s+', ' ', line)
        # join next line with space
        line = re.sub(r' \n', ' ', line)
        line = re.sub(r'.\n', '. ', line)
        line = re.sub(r'\x0c', ' ', line)
        
        pages_content.append(str(line).strip())

        # split paragraphs into well defined sentences using spacy
        for part in list(nlp(line).sents):
            sentences.append(str(part).strip())

#           sentences += nltk.sent_tokenize(line)
            
    # Only interested in full sentences and sentences with 10 to 100 words.
    sentences = [s for s in sentences if re.match('^[A-Z][^?!.]*[?.!]$', s) is not None]
    sentences = [s.replace('\n', ' ') for s in sentences]
    sentences = [s for s in sentences if (len(s.split(' ')) > 10) & (len(s.split(' ')) < 100)]

    return pages_content, sentences

Tokenization, Bigrams and Lemmatization¶

In [26]:
def run_NLP(content):

    def sent_to_words(sentences):
        for sentence in sentences:
            yield(gensim.utils.simple_preprocess(str(sentence), deacc=True))  # deacc=True removes punctuations

    # Define functions for stopwords, bigrams, trigrams and lemmatization
    def remove_stopwords(texts):
        return [[word for word in simple_preprocess(str(doc)) if word not in stop_words] for doc in texts]

    def make_bigrams(texts):
        return [bigram_mod[doc] for doc in texts]

    def make_trigrams(texts):
        return [trigram_mod[bigram_mod[doc]] for doc in texts]

    def lemmatization(texts, allowed_postags=['NOUN', 'ADJ', 'VERB', 'ADV']):
        """https://spacy.io/api/annotation"""
        texts_out = []
        for sent in texts:
            doc = nlp(" ".join(sent)) 
            texts_out.append([token.lemma_ for token in doc if token.pos_ in allowed_postags])
        return texts_out

    data_words = list(sent_to_words(content))

    # Build the bigram and trigram models
    bigram = gensim.models.Phrases(data_words, min_count=5, threshold=100) # higher threshold fewer phrases.
    trigram = gensim.models.Phrases(bigram[data_words], threshold=100)  

    # Faster way to get a sentence clubbed as a trigram/bigram
    bigram_mod = gensim.models.phrases.Phraser(bigram)
    trigram_mod = gensim.models.phrases.Phraser(trigram)

    # Remove Stop Words
    data_words_nostops = remove_stopwords(data_words)

    # Form Bigrams
    data_words_bigrams = make_bigrams(data_words_nostops)

    # Do lemmatization keeping only noun, adj, vb, adv
    data_lemmatized = lemmatization(data_words_bigrams, allowed_postags=['NOUN', 'ADJ', 'VERB', 'ADV'])
    
    return data_lemmatized

Using full text content in a page rather than full text content in a sentence here. A page defined as a document as per TFIDF calculation.

Topic Modeling and Latent Dirichlet Allocation (LDA)¶

Evaluaton Metrics

  1. Perplexity: Captures how surprised a model is of new data it has not seen before, and is measured as the normalized log-likelihood of a held-out test set. Lower the better.
  2. Coherence Score: Measures score a single topic by measuring the degree of semantic similarity between high scoring words in the topic. Higher the better.

In the analysis, the model with the highest coherence score is selected as the optimal model.

In [37]:

corpus = [id2word.doc2bow(text) for text in texts]

In [41]:
results = []
optimal_score = 0
optimal_model = None

for num_of_topics in tqdm(range(2,15,1)):
    
    result = {}
    
    # Build LDA model
    lda_model = gensim.models.ldamodel.LdaModel(corpus=corpus,
                                                id2word=id2word,
                                                num_topics=num_of_topics, 
                                                random_state=42,
                                                update_every=1,
                                                chunksize=5,
                                                passes=20,
                                                alpha='auto',
                                                per_word_topics=True) 

    coherence_model_lda = CoherenceModel(model=lda_model, texts=data_lemmatized, dictionary=id2word, coherence='c_v')
    
    if optimal_score < coherence_model_lda.get_coherence():
        optimal_score = coherence_model_lda.get_coherence()
        optimal_model = lda_model

    result['num_of_topics'] = num_of_topics
    result['perplexity'] = lda_model.log_perplexity(corpus)
    result['coherence_score'] = coherence_model_lda.get_coherence()
    
    results.append(result)
    
results = pd.DataFrame(results)  
results.set_index('num_of_topics', inplace=True)

cols = [color for name, color in mcolors.TABLEAU_COLORS.items()]  # more colors: 'mcolors.XKCD_COLORS'

cloud = WordCloud(stopwords=stop_words,
                  background_color='white',
                  width=2500,
                  height=1800,
                  max_words=50,
                  colormap='tab10',
                  color_func=lambda *args, **kwargs: cols[i],
                  prefer_horizontal=1.0)

topics = optimal_model.show_topics(formatted=False)

fig, axes = plt.subplots(1, 2, figsize=(15,15), sharex=True, sharey=True)

for i, ax in enumerate(axes.flatten()):
    fig.add_subplot(ax)
    topic_words = dict(topics[i][1])
    cloud.generate_from_frequencies(topic_words, max_font_size=300)
    plt.gca().imshow(cloud)
    plt.gca().set_title(topic_names[i], fontdict=dict(size=16))
    plt.gca().axis('off')


plt.subplots_adjust(wspace=0, hspace=0)
plt.axis('off')
plt.margins(x=0, y=0)
plt.tight_layout()
plt.show()

Closing Notes¶

  1. This is only a simple analysis that studies the ESG topics in only one ESG report. This study can be extended to more reports issued by the many companies across different sectors and industries.
  2. We can expect the number of topics to increase when more ESG reports are included in the study.
  3. Once relevant ESG topics are identified, then we can potentially calculate ESG scores by topics for all companies. Then we can assess and see whether such ESG score derived through NLP process correlates with the score given by rating agencies downloaded from yahoo finance.
